defaultCase F - defaultUnlawful arrest and police cautiondefaultKA is a 29 year old man from 
defaultBangladesh
default with no previous convictions, cautions or arrests
default. 
defaultKA had been living in the 
defaultUK
default on a spouse visa for less than 12 months
default. His relationship broke down leaving him without leave in the 
defaultUK
default and
default he
default would therefore have fallen foul of the residence test.
default&#xa0;
defaultKA suffered an assault and attended a police station to report this. Instead of his allegation being dealt with KA was arreste
defaultd on the basis that his assailant had attended the station a few hours previously and made an allegation of assault against him. 
default&#xa0;
defaultKA consistently denied committing an assault. Officers told him that if he admitted it he could go home but if he did not he 
defaultwould have to stay in custody for two to three months. KA signed a document which he later discovered had been a consent to a police caution.
default&#xa0;
defaultKA successfully challenged the lawfulness of the caution by way of judicial review proceedings. As a result of hi
defaults complaint the officers were disciplined and issued
default 
defaultwith
default 
defaultwritten
default 
defaultwarnings for unprofessional 
defaultbehaviour
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe police communicated incorrect information about the caution to the 
defaultUK
default Border Agency, seriously 
defaultjeopardising
default KA’s application for indefinite leave
default to remain. Upon KA’s challenge the information was rectified.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe claim settled for £20,000 plus an apology. KA was subsequently granted indefinite leave to remain. 
